name: 1,3-Diphenylpropane-1,3-dione
Reason:
The molecule 1,3-Diphenylpropane-1,3-dione contains the following structural elements: a propane-1,3-dione backbone and two phenyl groups. The effects of these groups on the melting point are as follows: 
- Propane: as a basic aliphatic hydrocarbon, would typically contribute to a low melting point compared to aromatic compounds. 
- Keto groups (C=O): these polar functional groups are capable of forming hydrogen bonds and generally contribute to an increase in the melting point when involved in a rigid molecular structure as observed here. 
- Phenyl groups: contribute to the rigidity and planarity of the molecule, which affects the crystalline packing; these aromatic rings generally increase the melting point due to enhanced pi-pi interactions. 
Considering the cumulative effect: 
- Base value for propane (low): +10. 
- Each keto group contributes significantly due to the ability to form hydrogen bonds and strong dipole-dipole interactions: +50 each. 
- Each phenyl group adds rigidity and pi-pi interactions, which can increase melting point significantly: +30 each. 
Adding these contributive effects should provide an estimate of the melting point.
Prediction: Base value (10) + Keto groups (2x50) + Phenyl groups (2x30) = 10 + 100 + 60 = 170°C
